Kevin IRL >:D 9/12/2023 3:27 PM
Dear Diary, I've been using Linux for literally, more than a year. It's been so fun there. I discovered the power of Free and Open Source Software, which unlocked so many possibilities of what I can do with my system. And to be completely honest, I hated Windows 10, because of the security updates, AND the fact it worked so slow previously. So I had to adjust it. But I didn't know how to install an another operating system. One day, I changed a registry setting which had the command "oobe.exe" to use the command "cmd.exe". And then, I restarted my computer, then tried to log in, but I couldn't because it looped without logging in. So I restarted the computer a number of times, got into the recovery option, then started to work my way to recovering my sessions. First I tried copying all of the files to my computer, then I flashed a Windows 7 image and tried to boot from it. It didn't work. I tried flashing the image several times, but it didn't work. I backed everything up after that. Later, I ran the Windows 7 installer. I was sure it wouldn't work, but it did! It showed the Windows 7 installer window! I quickly hit "Install Now", then installed Windows 7. Oh, it feels so good to be back on Windows 7! I installed VMWare Workstation 14 (the last version which supported Windows 7), created my first VM (Virtual Machine) with the disk, then tried Linux on it. I didn't have the courage to install it on my main computer, so I tried Linux on my VM. The first time I tried it, it was amazing, despite the minor issues I got with my VM. Later I watched Installation Tutorials on YouTube, then proceeded to install Debian Linux on my computer. I then did some distrohopping, learned some commands along the way, and would you look where I am now? I use Arch Linux, btw. Alright, I just wanna thank the developers of Audacity, Blender, Krita, GIMP, Inkscape, Firefox, Neovim, and so many other packages of software for making my life better on Linux. I hope to see you again real soon.
